item.title: U.S. to Cut Its Force in Iraq to About 3,000 Troops
item.description: The Trump administration will cut the number of U.S. troops in Iraq to about 3,000 this month, a top military commander said, a reduction from about 5,200 there now.

item.title: Ireland to Order Facebook to Stop Sending User Data to U.S.
item.description: Ireland’s privacy regulator is seeking Facebook’s response to a preliminary order to suspend the company’s data transfers to the U.S. because of concerns over American government surveillance practices

item.title: Fire Destroys Europe's Largest Migrant Camp, in Greece
item.description: Fire destroyed much of Europe’s largest camp for asylum seekers early Wednesday, as refugees and migrants on the Greek island of Lesbos protested against a lockdown imposed to contain a coronavirus outbreak.

item.title: Remote Learning in South Korea Becomes a Fixture of Pandemic Life
item.description: Parents, students and teachers in South Korea are contending with the consequences of a new Covid-19 outbreak in the country and adjusting to the reality that remote learning may be here for the foreseeable future.

item.title: With Navalny Sidelined, Russia's Opposition Seeks to Deal a Blow to Putin
item.description: Local elections later this week will provide a critical test of the Russian opposition’s staying power and whether the attack on Alexei Navalny has cowed or energized it.

item.title: Bomb Targets Afghanistan's Vice President as Kabul, Taliban Prepare for Historic Talks
item.description: A bombing targeting the convoy of Afghanistan’s first vice president killed at least 10 people in Kabul, an indication of the high stakes in the U.S.-backed talks to end nearly two decades of fighting.
